h3. Issue Summary

For a multi line custom field using the Wiki Style Renderer, clear out the values for the field value.

Search for the field in JQL within your project as 
{code:java}
customFieldName is not EMPTY AND project=YourProjectName{code}
This would still return the issues where the customFieldName has no value present.
h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Create a multi line text custom field. And use the wiki Style Renderer for this.
 # Input some value in this multi line text custom field within your issue.
 # Delete the value for the custom field.
 # Search in JQL, with the following query:
 ## 
{code:java}
customFieldName is not EMPTY AND project=YourProjectName{code}

 # It would return the above issue as well, where you just cleared out the value ( the one in step 3).

h3. Expected Results

The issue where the custom field value was deleted should not be listed.
h3. Actual Results

The issue where the custom field value was deleted is still getting listed.

In the HAR file, when clearing out the value from the custom field (customfield_10031) using the Wiki style renderer, the request contains the following:
{noformat}
{
  "fields": {
    "customfield_10031": {
      "type": "doc",
      "version": 1,
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "content": []
        }
      ]
    }
  }
}
{noformat}
Comparing this to the HAR file inputs for a custom field using the default text renderer, the request is:
{noformat}
 {
  "fields": {
    "customfield_10031": ""
  }
}
{noformat}
h3. Workaround

You can use the Default Text renderer instead of the WikiStyle Renderer and the search functionality works as expected.

h3. Problem 
As part of the [efforts to remove username|https://confluence.atlassian.com/cloud/blog/2018/06/say-goodbye-to-usernames-in-atlassian-cloud] in Cloud, some users are already configured with a UUID as the username. When those users are referenced in a JQL query (assignee/reporter), the data user information is not readable.

ie. 
{code}
assignee in (<UUID1>, <UUID2>)
{code}

h3. Suggested Solution 
The JQL should refer to readable user information.
ie. 

{code}
assignee in (<email_address1>, <email_address2>)
{code}

{code}
assignee in (<display_name1>, <display_name2>)
{code}

h3. Workaround
Run the JQL in Jira search and switch to Basic to retrieve the user information.
Run the JQL query and inspect the results to check for the user information.

For the activity stream, we use to be able to filter the API result with the username parameter. But since the changes for GDPR [Deprecation notice and migration guide for major changes to Jira Cloud REST APIs to improve user privacy|https://developer.atlassian.com/cloud/jira/platform/deprecation-notice-user-privacy-api-migration-guide/] 

The username parameter has been removed from the API and we no longer have the ability to filter the result by *username*

h4. Old behavior

The API can be filtered using the username as below:
{code}
https://<instance name>.atlassian.net/activity?streams=user+IS+<Username>&maxResults=100&os_Basic
{code}

h4. Suggestion
Ability to filter the API by account ID for instance
{code}
https://<instance name>.atlassian.net/activity?streams=accountId=<Account ID>&maxResults=100&os_Basic{code}
